<node id="eGFR">
  <data key="d0">eGFR</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">eGFR (estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate) is a measure of kidney function, with values classified as &lt;90 mL/min/1.73 m2 indicating reduced function.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Creatinine eGFR">
  <data key="d0">Creatinine eGFR</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Creatinine eGFR is an estimate of kidney function based on serum creatinine levels, used in propionic acidemia patients.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Propionic Acidemia (PA) Patients">
  <data key="d0">Propionic Acidemia (PA) Patients</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Propionic acidemia patients are individuals with a genetic metabolic disorder, studied for renal function in the NIH cohort.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="National Institutes of Health (NIH) Propionic Acidemia Cohort">
  <data key="d0">National Institutes of Health (NIH) Propionic Acidemia Cohort</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">The NIH Propionic Acidemia Cohort is a study group of patients with propionic acidemia, providing demographics, genetics, and renal-related findings.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fisher's Exact Test">
  <data key="d0">Fisher's Exact Test</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Fisher's exact test is a statistical method used to analyze the classification of eGFR values, yielding a P value &lt;0.0001.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Regression Lines">
  <data key="d0">Regression Lines</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Regression lines compare creatinine eGFR and cystatin C eGFR in nontransplanted patients, showing differences in intercepts and slopes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nontransplanted Patients">
  <data key="d0">Nontransplanted Patients</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Nontransplanted patients are propionic acidemia patients who have not undergone liver transplantation, analyzed for eGFR trends.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b8a835d63382015bc0073fd6f79ae0ba</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="1,25-OH-Vitamin D">
  <data key="d0">1,25-OH-Vitamin D</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">1,25-OH-Vitamin D is a laboratory parameter measured in the study, with low levels found in 2 out of 31 participants.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Intact Parathyroid Hormone (PTH)">
  <data key="d0">Intact Parathyroid Hormone (PTH)</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Intact parathyroid hormone (PTH) is a laboratory parameter measured in the study, with elevated levels found in 3 out of 31 participants.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Erythropoietin">
  <data key="d0">Erythropoietin</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Erythropoietin is a laboratory parameter measured in the study, with elevated levels found in 7 out of 27 subjects, correlating with bone marrow suppression.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="24-Hour Creatinine Clearance">
  <data key="d0">24-Hour Creatinine Clearance</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">24-hour creatinine clearance is a laboratory parameter used to assess renal function in the study.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Abdominal Ultrasound">
  <data key="d0">Abdominal Ultrasound</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Abdominal ultrasound is an imaging technique used in the study to examine renal anatomy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Transthoracic Echocardiography">
  <data key="d0">Transthoracic Echocardiography</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Transthoracic echocardiography is an imaging technique used in the study to assess cardiac function.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-83724ab6403639b1149ca8570bc6e741</data>
  <data key="d4">shchelochkov2019.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780045995</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ilow SW">
  <data key="d0">Ilow SW</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Ilow SW is an author of the work "Urea cycle enzymes" published in "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Horwich AL">
  <data key="d0">Horwich AL</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Horwich AL is a co-author of the work "Urea cycle enzymes" published in "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Scriver CR">
  <data key="d0">Scriver CR</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Scriver CR is an editor of the book "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Beaudet AL">
  <data key="d0">Beaudet AL</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Beaudet AL is an editor of "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases" and a co-author of works on argininosuccinate synthetase and gene transfer.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Sly WS">
  <data key="d0">Sly WS</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Sly WS is an editor of the book "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Valle D">
  <data key="d0">Valle D</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Valle D is an editor of the book "The metabolic basis of inherited diseases".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="The Metabolic Basis of Inherited Diseases">
  <data key="d0">The Metabolic Basis of Inherited Diseases</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">The Metabolic Basis of Inherited Diseases is a book, 6th edition, published by McGraw-Hill in 1989, containing the chapter "Urea cycle enzymes".</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bachmann C">
  <data key="d0">Bachmann C</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Bachmann C is an author of the article on N-acetylglutamate synthetase deficiency published in the New England Journal of Medicine.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Krahenbuhl S">
  <data key="d0">Krahenbuhl S</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Krahenbuhl S is a co-author of</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-795f0f50f5083382c49b397ac4a29a01</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Liver Transplantation">
  <data key="d0">Liver Transplantation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Liver transplantation is a surgical procedure used to correct metabolic consequences of urea cycle deficiencies, as established by cumulative experience in multiple cases.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Urea Cycle Deficiencies">
  <data key="d0">Urea Cycle Deficiencies</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Urea cycle deficiencies are metabolic disorders for which liver transplantation has been shown to be effective, correcting metabolic consequences beyond alternative therapies.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Enzyme Replacement Therapy">
  <data key="d0">Enzyme Replacement Therapy</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Enzyme replacement therapy is a potential future treatment approach for urea cycle deficiencies, envisioned as a step beyond whole-liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Virus-Mediated Gene Transfer">
  <data key="d0">Virus-Mediated Gene Transfer</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Virus-mediated gene transfer is a technique involving the introduction of functional complementary DNA into cells, accomplished in rodents for human ASS.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Human ASS">
  <data key="d0">Human ASS</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Human ASS (argininosuccinate synthetase) is a gene that has been successfully transferred via virus-mediated methods in rodents, suggesting potential therapeutic applications.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hepatocyte Transplantation">
  <data key="d0">Hepatocyte Transplantation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Hepatocyte transplantation is a cell-based therapy considered as an alternative to whole-liver transplantation for treating metabolic diseases.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dietary Protein Restriction">
  <data key="d0">Dietary Protein Restriction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Dietary protein restriction is a conventional treatment for urea cycle deficiencies, but is less effective than liver transplantation in correcting metabolic consequences.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Alternative Pathways of Waste Nitrogen Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Alternative Pathways of Waste Nitrogen Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Alternative pathways of waste nitrogen synthesis and excretion are therapeutic approaches that are less effective than liver transplantation for correcting metabolic consequences.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5cae78531cd9206479ead804b11684d1</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hyperammonemia">
  <data key="d0">Hyperammonemia</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Hyperammonemia is a metabolic condition characterized by elevated ammonia levels in the blood, corrected by liver transplantation in the patients described.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plasma Amino Acid Abnormalities">
  <data key="d0">Plasma Amino Acid Abnormalities</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Plasma amino acid abnormalities refer to deviations from normal levels of amino acids in the blood, corrected by orthotopic liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Standard Liver Function Abnormalities">
  <data key="d0">Standard Liver Function Abnormalities</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Standard liver function abnormalities are deviations in typical liver function tests, corrected by orthotopic liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Orthotopic Liver Transplantation">
  <data key="d0">Orthotopic Liver Transplantation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Orthotopic liver transplantation is a surgical procedure that replaces a diseased liver with a healthy donor liver, used to correct metabolic abnormalities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="14-Day-Old Boy">
  <data key="d0">14-Day-Old Boy</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">A 14-day-old boy with carbamyl phosphate synthetase-I deficiency who underwent orthotopic liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Carbamyl Phosphate Synthetase-I Deficiency">
  <data key="d0">Carbamyl Phosphate Synthetase-I Deficiency</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Carbamyl phosphate synthetase-I deficiency is a urea cycle enzyme deficiency causing hyperammonemia and metabolic abnormalities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="35-Year-Old Man">
  <data key="d0">35-Year-Old Man</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">A 35-year-old man with argininosuccinic acid synthetase deficiency who underwent orthotopic liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Argininosuccinic Acid Synthetase Deficiency">
  <data key="d0">Argininosuccinic Acid Synthetase Deficiency</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Argininosuccinic acid synthetase deficiency is a urea cycle enzyme deficiency causing hyperammonemia and metabolic abnormalities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-344323b918fd0a2f63161ea908593c80</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Patient 1">
  <data key="d0">Patient 1</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Patient 1 is a subject who underwent surgery and had normal plasma amino acid levels 34 months post-surgery, with detectable citrulline levels. The native liver showed minor nonspecific abnormalities on light microscopy and normal electron microscopy except for nonspecific mitochondrial elongation. CPS-I activity was undetectable in the liver homogenate.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-fc8300849246981a965ff70c583daf4d</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Patient 2">
  <data key="d0">Patient 2</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Patient 2 is a subject whose plasma amino acids before and after transplantation are summarized in Table 2. Preoperative high citrulline and modest arginine elevations were corrected postoperatively, but ornithine levels were slightly elevated at 3 and 20 months. The native liver was enlarged with cholestasis, massive steatosis, and hemosiderosis, with periportal fibrosis but no cirrhosis. The liver homogenate was devoid of ASS activity but had significant CPS-1, OTC, and AS activity.&lt;SEP&gt;Patient 2 is a subject whose urea cycle enzyme activities and plasma amino acid levels were analyzed before and after liver transplantation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-fc8300849246981a965ff70c583daf4d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e776f44c2a2b63585778263cf8b4315</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Citrulline">
  <data key="d0">Citrulline</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Citrulline is an amino acid that became detectable in Patient 1 after surgery and was present at extremely high preoperative levels in Patient 2, which were corrected postoperatively.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-fc8300849246981a965ff70c583daf4d</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Arginine">
  <data key="d0">Arginine</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Arginine is an amino acid that showed modest elevations preoperatively in Patient 2, which were corrected at all measured postoperative times.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-fc8300849246981a965ff70c583daf4d</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ornithine">
  <data key="d0">Ornithine</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Ornithine is an amino acid with a normal range of 40 to 100 μmol/L. In Patient 2, it was slightly elevated at 3 months (153 μmol/L) and 20 months (124 μmol/L) postoperatively.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-fc8300849246981a965ff70c583daf4d</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Urea Cycle Enzymes">
  <data key="d0">Urea Cycle Enzymes</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Urea cycle enzymes include CPS-I, OTC, ASS, and AS, which were analyzed in liver tissues from Patient 2.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1e776f44c2a2b63585778263cf8b4315</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="CPS-I">
  <data key="d0">CPS-I</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">CPS-I is a urea cycle enzyme whose activity was measured in the liver tissue of Patient 2.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1e776f44c2a2b63585778263cf8b4315</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="OTC">
  <data key="d0">OTC</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">OTC is a urea cycle enzyme whose activity was measured in the liver tissue of Patient 2.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1e776f44c2a2b63585778263cf8b4315</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ASS">
  <data key="d0">ASS</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">ASS is a urea cycle enzyme whose activity was measured in the liver tissue of Patient 2.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1e776f44c2a2b63585778263cf8b4315</data>
  <data key="d4">todo1992.pdf</data>
  <data key="d5">1780046012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="AS">
  <data key="d0">AS</data>
